{
  "text": "The possible role of NA in long-distance Fe transport in the xylem is still being explored [CITATION_1] ). However, strong evidence supports that this amino acid is not essential for xylem Fe transport: the NA-deficient tomato mutant chloronerva does accumulate Fe in old leaves [CITATION_2] and the A. thaliana NA synthase (NAS) quadruple mutant (with low levels of NA) also accumulates Fe in leaves [CITATION_3] . Until now, Fe-NA chelates have not been detected in xylem sap [CITATION_4] , and in silico and/or in vitro speciation studies tend to exclude NA as a possible xylem Fe carrier at the slightly acidic pH values typical of xylem [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . However, it has been recently suggested that NA may play a role in long distance transport of Fe when carboxylates are in short supply, as it occurs in FRD mutants [CITATION_7] or in plant species with less acidic xylem such in field-grown Prunus persica trees (where the xylem sap pH is in the range from 6.5 to 7.5 [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . The most accepted role of NA is in intra-organ Fe distribution, where this ligand could be crucial for xylem Fe unloading. Iron distribution within leaves is impeded in the tomato mutant chloronerva [CITATION_10] ) that also showed a lower presence of Fe(II) ions in the veins when leaves were analyzed by XANES [CITATION_11] . This suggests that the occurrence of Fe as Fe(II)-NA complex in leaf veins is crucial for the intra-organ Fe allocation [CITATION_12] . No transporter responsible for moving Fe-complexes into the xylem sap has been conclusively identified so far, but it has been suggested that Fe-NA could be effluxed into the xylem by a yellow-stripe-like (YSL) transporter [CITATION_13] . Regarding PSs, only a minor peak assigned to Fe(III)-DMA was found in press sap from the roots of Fe-deficient wheat plants by HILIC-ESI-MS [CITATION_14] .",
